Today I order skirt steak and other things. Bill was $100. Before I ordered I asked if they took Apple Pay which they said they did. When we went to pay their machine wasn't working. My friend and I tried our Apple Pay and machine kept taking us to card reader error for chip malfunction. We left a $20 tip on the table ( 20% of bill ) offered to leave $50 additional cash while we went and got cash, the guy refused and said he needed some sort of I.D and he couldn't let us go without it. I told him that that is very wrong bc we are willing to pay, it wasn't our fault. We always order from there and eat there. Today was our last day giving them our business. I am sure there are multiple restaurants in this area willing to take our business. I will never order, or eat at this place again. We then came and pay the bill in full in cash, got our I.d backs. I'm sure if we were dressed like lawyers and were white this would have never happened. Do not come here if brown/black.

This "blast from the past" comes with a side of prejudice and downright viciousness.  This is the first review I've ever felt I needed to write — but Clark's is (quite deliberately) responsible for one of the sadder moments I can remember in New York:  I've come to Clark's most weeks for years, sometimes three times per week.  Yesterday, I came in about 10:45, ordered a coffee and a bagel, waited for a friend.   When he came — a Hasidic guy, in traditional Jewish clothing — he ordered a coffee.  They brought the check without bringing his coffee, though we hadn't said we were leaving.  It was under the $10 minimum — something like $7. I left $13 (and we asked again for the second coffee).  It was about 12:30.  The owner/manager comes back (immediately enraged, no diplomacy, no attempt to speak to us as people), shouting "you've been here since nine in the morning."  He ignored me every time I asked him why he would say that, so deliberately, so confidently, when he saw me come in just before 11.  He tells us my friend needs to order more.  I say that he keeps kosher, and that's all he can eat. The man says: "Then this isn't the place for you."  He said: "you are an embarrassment." (Because I left a 100% tip on a small bill? Or because of our ethnicities — mine far more "passing", my friend's far more obvious?)  I should say: the place was 2/3 empty the entire time we were there, perhaps half-full at the max.  This place is an embarrassment.  A place that hides old fashioned racism under the more fashionable prejudice, that a person is only "worth" what they spend on a given day.  Sure, they forgot how much I really have given them, how often I've eaten their stale toast and cardboard eggs just to be in blast-from-the-past New York.  Seems like they're stuck farther in the past than I ever knew — and I'll never be back.
